A screenshot of PHP code.

This is fun because it technically allows soft-deleting absolutely *any* entity configured in the project that has the "setDeletedAt()" PHP method.

This is sarcastic fun because it's a major security flaw.

Here is the code:

<?php

namespace App\Controller;

use Doctrine\Persistence\ManagerRegistry;
use Symfony\Bundle\FrameworkBundle\Controller\AbstractController;

/**
 * Class SoftDeleteController
 */
class SoftDeleteController extends AbstractController
{
    public function __construct(private ManagerRegistry $doctrine) {}

    /**
     * @param  object  $data
     * @return object
     */
    public function __invoke(object $data): object
    {
        if (method_exists($data, 'setDeletedAt')) {
            $manager = $this->doctrine->getManagerForClass(get_class($data));
            $data->setDeletedAt();
            $manager->flush();
        }

        return $data;
    }
}

